When Jim overhears that he is about to be sold to a man in New Orleans, separated from his wife and daughter forever, he runs away until he can formulate a plan. Meanwhile, Huck has faked his own death to escape his violent father. As all readers of American literature know, thus begins the dangerous and transcendent journey by raft down the Mississippi River toward the elusive and unreliable promise of the Free States and beyond.

Brimming with nuanced humor and lacerating observations that have made Everett a literary icon, this brilliant and tender novel radically illuminates Jim''s agency, intelligence, and compassion as never before. James is destined to be a major publishing event and a cornerstone of twenty-first-century American literature.', 'This reimagining of Huckleberry Finn centers on enslaved Jim, who flees sale and separation from his family, rafting down the Mississippi with Huck amid dangers and deceptions.', 2024, '0593862732', '9780593686867', 320, NULL, 469, 'https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/id/15094964-L.jpg', '/works/OL36506504W', NULL, '2024', 'English', NULL, 1, 0, 'james-percival-l-everett', 0, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'public', '2026-03-16 07:16:09', '2026-03-23 04:12:04');
